{
  "doc_id": "32026",
  "text": "We also assayed Sse1's mode of action in GA-induced degradation of Ste11⌬N K444R . Although reintroduction of WT SSE1 or sse1-K69Q completely restored fast kinase degradation to sse1⌬ cells, the G233D mutant did not ( Figure  3C ). Together, these results demonstrate that the Hsp70-binding and NEF activity of Sse1 is required to support productive maturation of these Hsp90 client proteins. Moreover, this mechanistic insight into Sse1 function extends to the triage decision occurring in the presence of GA, as the sse1-G233D mutant is unable to promote rapid degradation of Ste11⌬N K444R . Other yeast proteins act as NEFs for cytosolic Hsp70 chaperones in addition to Sse1. One of these is Sse2, a less abundant paralog of Sse1 that can compensate for some Sse1 functions when overexpressed [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Another is Snl1, which contains a mammalian Bag domain and can function as an Hsp70 NEF [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Snl1 is anchored to the cytoplasmic face of the endoplasmic reticulum through an amino-terminal transmembrane domain. Truncation of this domain (Snl1⌬N) renders the protein soluble and retains NEF activity [CITATION_5] . We therefore asked whether Sse1 functions in GR maturation and whether regulation of Ste11⌬N K444R degradation could be replaced by these other yeast NEFs. Overexpression of the SSE2 and SNL1⌬N genes both effectively suppressed the slow-growth phenotype of sse1⌬ cells at 30°C ( Figure 4A ). In contrast, only SSE2 permitted growth at the more restrictive temperature of 39°C. We established previously that this hightemperature growth phenotype is due to severe reduction in signaling through the cell integrity pathway because of loss of Slt2 (Mpk1) kinase activity in strains compromised for Sse1 function [CITATION_6] . Slt2 is an Hsp90 client; thus the observed growth defect of sse1⌬ cells at 39°C is a direct consequence of Sse1's participation in Hsp90 chaperoning [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Consistent with this result, Sse2 completely restored GR activation, whereas Snl1⌬N only partially suppressed loss of Sse1 ( Figure 4B ). These results were further mirrored when Ste11⌬N K444R degradation kinetics were measured in the presence of the different NEFs: Sse2 restored fast degradation to sse1⌬ cells, whereas overexpression of SNL1⌬N resulted in a half-life intermediate between that observed with sse1⌬ and WT cells ( Figure 4C ). Thus, although unrelated NEFs can compensate for at least some of Sse1's in vivo roles, as evidenced by suppression of the 30°C slow growth phenotype of sse1⌬ cells, only the Hsp110 family, composed in budding yeast of ",
